{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5067adcb-0103-4efe-88bd-7d74cdbf8799","content":"**Yes, it works perfectly.** Both `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>` can be created via `stackalloc`:\n\n```csharp\nSpan<nint>  nints  = stackalloc nint[4];\nSpan<nuint> nuints = stackalloc nuint[3];\n```\n\nOutput on this 64-bit system:\n\n```\nnint span:  [42, 9223372036854775807, 0, 0]   // nint.MaxValue = Int64.MaxValue\nnuint span: [99, 18446744073709551615, 0]      // nuint.MaxValue = UInt64.MaxValue\n```\n\n`nint`/`nuint` (native-sized integers, introduced in C# 9) are valid unmanaged types, so they satisfy the `stackalloc` constraint. The actual size follows the platform pointer width (8 bytes here on x64).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"43983f74-42df-4827-9857-8026b3ddf200","outputTokens":226,"requestId":"FE00:56E5A:13CA32B:162B344:6A067017"},"id":"0259103a-c11c-44fc-a919-849ae184a234","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:00:13.343Z","parentId":"93536e02-8d1b-4fe0-8c9a-c76eb2e413e8"}
